00:37:47,309 --> 00:37:51,370
Berg, I don't mean to distract you, but
we're meant to study Homer, not Sophie.

260
00:38:00,389 --> 00:38:02,721
- It's wonderful, isn't it?
- Wonderful.

261
00:38:02,791 --> 00:38:04,315
It's gonna be a great summer.

262
00:38:18,440 --> 00:38:21,307
- Why do you leave early?
- He always leaves early.

263
00:38:21,376 --> 00:38:24,607
- Do you have somewhere to go?
- See you tomorrow.

264
00:38:33,088 --> 00:38:35,147
Sorry I'm late.

265
00:38:37,259 --> 00:38:39,227
I got held up at school.

266
00:38:41,229 --> 00:38:42,958
I have a new book.

267
00:38:43,031 --> 00:38:46,194
<i>The Lady with a Little Dog.</i>

268
00:38:48,804 --> 00:38:50,066
By Anton Chekhov.

269
00:38:50,138 --> 00:38:53,437
"The talk was that a new face
had appeared on the promenade,

270
00:38:53,508 --> 00:38:55,669
a lady with a little dog."

271
00:39:08,357 --> 00:39:10,882
Schmitz, one moment, please.

272
00:39:12,260 --> 00:39:16,424
I read the reports on you.
Every single one. Excellent work.

273
00:39:16,498 --> 00:39:19,092
You'll be working in the office.

274
00:39:19,167 --> 00:39:22,534
You got promoted. Congratulations.

275
00:39:29,745 --> 00:39:33,704
- Yee-haw!
- Ah!

276
00:39:33,782 --> 00:39:35,977
Let's get out of here!

277
00:39:36,051 --> 00:39:39,384
Come on! Michael, we're leaving.
Let's go!

278
00:39:39,454 --> 00:39:40,580
Come on, Michael!

279
00:39:40,656 --> 00:39:43,682
It's meant to be a surprise
for your birthday.

280
00:39:47,262 --> 00:39:49,457
- Come on!
- What's the matter?

281
00:39:49,531 --> 00:39:52,694
- I'm sorry. Really.
- We thought you'd like it.

282
00:39:52,768 --> 00:39:54,963
We've got beer!
We're gonna dance!

283
00:39:55,937 --> 00:39:57,029
I promised someone.

284
00:39:58,173 --> 00:40:00,164
Michael, please!

285
00:40:05,280 --> 00:40:08,943
"Here and there the reflection
of the stars and the lights,

286
00:40:09,017 --> 00:40:11,417
on the bank quivered and trembled."

287
00:40:11,486 --> 00:40:14,182
- Oh, kid, kid.
- What?

288
00:40:14,256 --> 00:40:17,157
- Stop.
- What's wrong now?

289
00:40:17,225 --> 00:40:19,750
Nothing's wrong.

290
00:40:22,330 --> 00:40:24,093
It's nothing.

291
00:40:26,201 --> 00:40:29,602
You know, you never ask.

292
00:40:30,272 --> 00:40:33,264
You never bother to ask how I am!

293
00:40:33,341 --> 00:40:35,002
You never say.

294
00:40:36,311 --> 00:40:38,142
It just happens to be my birthday.

295
00:40:39,981 --> 00:40:42,711
It's my birthday, that's all!

296
00:40:42,784 --> 00:40:44,684
You've never
even asked when it is.

297
00:40:44,753 --> 00:40:47,449
- If you want a fight, kid...
- I don't want a fight!

298
00:40:47,522 --> 00:40:51,117
- What's wrong with you?!
- What business is it of yours?!

299
00:40:51,193 --> 00:40:54,560
It's always on your terms.
Everything.

300
00:40:54,629 --> 00:40:57,359
We do what you want.
It's always what you want.

301
00:40:57,432 --> 00:41:00,230
- My friends were giving me a party.
- Why are you here?

302
00:41:00,302 --> 00:41:03,965
Go back to your party.
Is that what you want?

303
00:41:06,308 --> 00:41:08,503
Mm! Mm!

304
00:41:29,631 --> 00:41:31,599
It's always me
that has to apologize.

305
00:41:31,666 --> 00:41:35,966
You don't have to apologize.
No one has to apologize.

306
00:41:44,679 --> 00:41:46,408
<i>War and Peace,</i> kid.

307
00:43:31,786 --> 00:43:34,016
Now, you must go
back to your friends.

308
00:43:50,205 --> 00:43:51,194
Are you all right?

309
00:45:22,364 --> 00:45:23,695
It's him.

310
00:45:27,635 --> 00:45:29,796
Good.

311
00:45:29,871 --> 00:45:32,169
Get the boy something to eat.

312
00:45:41,182 --> 00:45:44,743
I think we all knew you'd
come back to us eventually.

313
00:46:53,855 --> 00:46:57,018
Mr. Berg? It is 8:00.

314
00:46:57,092 --> 00:46:58,855
Your daughter.

315
00:47:01,496 --> 00:47:03,623
Thank you.

316
00:47:06,267 --> 00:47:08,098
Julia.

317
00:47:10,205 --> 00:47:13,265
- I've not kept you waiting?
- I was early.

318
00:47:13,341 --> 00:47:15,571
Welcome back.

319
00:47:18,313 --> 00:47:21,441
So how will you decide?

320
00:47:21,516 --> 00:47:24,349
I don't know.

321
00:47:24,419 --> 00:47:26,319
I'm happy back in Berlin, I suppose.

322
00:47:26,387 --> 00:47:28,548
- You've seen your mother?
- Mm-hmm.

323
00:47:28,623 --> 00:47:31,251
I wanted to get away. That's all.

324
00:47:31,326 --> 00:47:33,760
It was Paris,
but it could have been anywhere.

325
00:47:33,828 --> 00:47:36,296
Away from your parents?

326
00:47:38,166 --> 00:47:40,600
I'm aware I was difficult.

327
00:47:42,437 --> 00:47:44,268
I wasn't always open with you.

328
00:47:47,809 --> 00:47:50,107
I'm not open with anyone.

329
00:47:56,618 --> 00:47:58,176
I knew you were distant.

330
00:48:00,054 --> 00:48:04,991
You know...
I always assumed it was my fault.

331
00:48:06,060 --> 00:48:08,858
Julia.

332
00:48:08,930 --> 00:48:10,659
How wrong can you be?

333
00:48:22,410 --> 00:48:25,311
- I'll see you very soon.
- See you soon.

334
00:48:28,049 --> 00:48:30,609
- Good night, Dad.
- Good night.

335
00:48:38,359 --> 00:48:40,987
Those of you
for the special seminar group,

336
00:48:41,062 --> 00:48:43,193
please stay on in this room.

337
00:48:43,264 --> 00:48:46,028
Professor Rohl will
be here in a moment.

338
00:49:16,698 --> 00:49:21,567
Well, we seem
to be quite a small group.

339
00:49:21,636 --> 00:49:25,367
A small group and a select one.

340
00:49:25,440 --> 00:49:28,773
Clearly, this is going
to be a unique seminar.

341
00:49:28,843 --> 00:49:33,371
We are going to start
with a reading list, gentlemen.

342
00:49:33,448 --> 00:49:35,973
Karl Jaspers...

343
00:49:36,050 --> 00:49:40,350
- And ladies.
- <i>... The Question of German Guilt.</i>

344
00:49:40,421 --> 00:49:44,323
<i></i>

345
00:49:56,904 --> 00:49:59,896
So this is where you are.

346
00:49:59,974 --> 00:50:01,498
Yes.

347
00:50:03,311 --> 00:50:04,778
Come in.

348
00:50:06,881 --> 00:50:10,612
- You take work seriously.
- I don't know.

349
00:50:10,685 --> 00:50:13,119
You're rather a serious boy.

350
00:50:13,187 --> 00:50:15,280
It's how I was brought up.

351
00:50:16,858 --> 00:50:19,952
What about you? Are you serious?

352
00:50:22,830 --> 00:50:25,298
You're sure you want to work tonight?

353
00:50:26,834 --> 00:50:27,994
Yeah.

354
00:50:29,737 --> 00:50:31,364
But I won't work every night.

355
00:50:32,540 --> 00:50:34,098
See you tomorrow.

356
00:50:40,081 --> 00:50:43,175
- Yes. Exactly
- That's right.

357
00:50:47,989 --> 00:50:49,820
You need a hand.

358
00:51:14,682 --> 00:51:18,846
- Why all the police?
- They're worried about demonstrators.

359
00:51:18,920 --> 00:51:21,787
- For or against?
- Both.

360
00:51:27,228 --> 00:51:28,718
Wow. It's a circus.

361
00:51:31,999 --> 00:51:33,899
All rise.

362
00:51:36,504 --> 00:51:38,870
All photographers
are now asked to leave.

363
00:51:40,274 --> 00:51:43,072
This court is now in session.
Please sit down.

364
00:51:46,581 --> 00:51:49,106
First thing I'm going to do
is hear motions

365
00:51:49,183 --> 00:51:51,378
from each of the defendants' lawyers.

366
00:51:51,452 --> 00:51:55,286
They're arguing that there's
no reason to keep the defendants in jail

367
00:51:55,356 --> 00:51:58,052
until the outcome
of the forthcoming trial.

368
00:51:58,126 --> 00:52:00,788
- I'll take these cases one by one.
- Want a pen?

369
00:52:00,862 --> 00:52:04,161
- I got a pen.
- Hanna Schmitz.

370
00:52:05,800 --> 00:52:09,600
- Your name is Hanna Schmitz?
- Yes.

371
00:52:09,670 --> 00:52:12,036
Can you speak louder please?

372
00:52:12,106 --> 00:52:15,166
- My name is Hanna Schmitz.
- Thank you.

373
00:52:15,243 --> 00:52:21,079
- You were born on October 21 st, 1922?
- Yes.

374
00:52:21,149 --> 00:52:22,980
At Hermannstadt.

375
00:52:23,050 --> 00:52:27,384
- And you're now 43 years old?
- Yes.

376
00:52:27,455 --> 00:52:32,552
- You joined the SS in 1943?
- Yes.

377
00:52:32,627 --> 00:52:35,187
What was your
reason for joining?

378
00:52:36,898 --> 00:52:40,026
You were working
at the Siemens factory at the time?

379
00:52:40,101 --> 00:52:41,193
Yes.

380
00:52:41,269 --> 00:52:43,863
You'd recently
been offered a promotion.

381
00:52:43,938 --> 00:52:45,803
Why did you prefer to join the SS?

382
00:52:45,873 --> 00:52:49,138
- Objection.
- I'll re-phrase my question.

383
00:52:49,210 --> 00:52:51,804
I'm trying to ascertain

384
00:52:51,879 --> 00:52:54,939
if she joined the SS freely, hmm?

385
00:52:55,016 --> 00:52:56,449
Of her own free will.

386
00:52:58,052 --> 00:53:01,613
- I heard there were jobs.
- Go on.

387
00:53:01,689 --> 00:53:04,522
I was working at Siemens

388
00:53:04,592 --> 00:53:07,857
when I heard the SS was recruiting.

389
00:53:07,929 --> 00:53:11,797
Did you know the kind of work
you'd be expected to do?

390
00:53:11,866 --> 00:53:15,495
They were looking for guards.

391
00:53:15,570 --> 00:53:19,836
- I applied for a job.
- You worked first at Auschwitz?

392
00:53:19,907 --> 00:53:23,172
- Yes.
- Until 1944.

393
00:53:23,244 --> 00:53:27,840
Then you were moved to
a smaller camp near Krak×£w?

394
00:53:27,915 --> 00:53:29,507
- Yes.
- Are you OK?

395
00:53:29,584 --> 00:53:32,314
- You helped move prisoners...
- I'm fine.

396
00:53:32,386 --> 00:53:35,844
...west in the winter of 1944
in the so-called death marches?

397
00:53:57,111 --> 00:54:00,808
- So, what did you think?
- I don't know.

398
00:54:02,049 --> 00:54:04,017
It wasn't quite what I was expecting.

399
00:54:04,085 --> 00:54:08,385
Wasn't it? In what way?
What were you expecting?

400
00:54:08,456 --> 00:54:10,788
I thought it was exciting.

401
00:54:10,858 --> 00:54:13,349
Exciting? Why?

402
00:54:13,427 --> 00:54:15,895
Why did you think it was exciting?

403
00:54:15,963 --> 00:54:17,692
Because it's justice.

404
00:54:46,928 --> 00:54:52,457
Societies think they operate
by something called morality,

405
00:54:52,533 --> 00:54:54,023
but they don't.

406
00:54:54,101 --> 00:54:58,470
They operate by something called law.

407
00:54:58,539 --> 00:55:04,171
You're not guilty of anything
merely by working at Auschwitz.

408
00:55:04,245 --> 00:55:07,510
Eight thousand people
worked at Auschwitz.

409
00:55:07,582 --> 00:55:13,077
Precisely 19 have been convicted,
and only six for murder.

410
00:55:13,154 --> 00:55:18,114
To prove murder,
you have to prove intent.

411
00:55:18,192 --> 00:55:20,023
That's the law.

412
00:55:20,094 --> 00:55:23,825
The question is never was it wrong,

413
00:55:23,898 --> 00:55:26,765
but was it legal.

414
00:55:26,834 --> 00:55:31,601
And not by our laws, no.

415
00:55:31,672 --> 00:55:35,768
- By the laws at the time.
- But isn't that...

416
00:55:35,843 --> 00:55:38,368
- What?
...narrow?

417
00:55:38,446 --> 00:55:42,314
Oh, yes. The law is narrow.

418
00:55:43,317 --> 00:55:45,478
On the other hand,

419
00:55:45,553 --> 00:55:49,011
I suspect people who kill other people

420
00:55:49,090 --> 00:55:52,719
tend to be aware that it's wrong.

421
00:55:53,794 --> 00:55:58,224
Miss Schmitz,
you're familiar with this book?

422
00:56:00,334 --> 00:56:02,598
- Yes.
- Parts of it

423
00:56:02,670 --> 00:56:05,138
have already been
read out in court.

424
00:56:05,206 --> 00:56:07,800
It's by a survivor,

425
00:56:07,875 --> 00:56:09,809
a prisoner who survived.

426
00:56:09,877 --> 00:56:12,607
Ilana Mather.

427
00:56:12,680 --> 00:56:15,342
She was in the camp
when she was a child, wasn't she?

428
00:56:15,416 --> 00:56:18,112
- She was with her mother.
- Yes.

429
00:56:18,185 --> 00:56:22,519
In the book,
she describes a selection process.

430
00:56:22,590 --> 00:56:25,616
At the end of the month's labor,
every month,

431
00:56:25,693 --> 00:56:28,753
sixty inmates were selected.

432
00:56:28,829 --> 00:56:32,321
Picked out to be sent from
the satellite camp back to Auschwitz.

433
00:56:32,400 --> 00:56:34,334
That's right, isn't it?

434
00:56:35,703 --> 00:56:37,933
Yes, that's right.

435
00:56:38,005 --> 00:56:41,406
And, so far,
each of your fellow defendants

436
00:56:41,475 --> 00:56:44,273
has specifically denied
being part of that process.

437
00:56:44,345 --> 00:56:48,304
Now, I'm going to ask you.

438
00:56:48,382 --> 00:56:49,747
Were you part of it?

439
00:56:52,286 --> 00:56:53,310
Yes.

440
00:56:56,891 --> 00:57:00,486
So you helped make the selection?

441
00:57:00,561 --> 00:57:03,553
- Yes.
- You admit that?

442
00:57:09,036 --> 00:57:12,233
Then tell me,

443
00:57:12,306 --> 00:57:14,706
how did that selection happen?

444
00:57:14,775 --> 00:57:17,471
There were six guards,

445
00:57:17,545 --> 00:57:22,175
so we decided we'd
choose ten people each.

446
00:57:23,751 --> 00:57:26,413
That's how we did it every month.

447
00:57:26,487 --> 00:57:28,717
We'd all choose ten.

448
00:57:28,789 --> 00:57:31,519
Your fellow defendants
took part in the process?

449
00:57:31,592 --> 00:57:34,356
We all did.

450
00:57:34,428 --> 00:57:37,090
Even though they've denied it?

451
00:57:37,164 --> 00:57:40,895
Saying "we," "we all"
is easier than saying "I," "I alone,"

452
00:57:40,968 --> 00:57:42,663
isn't it, Miss Schmitz?

453
00:57:44,305 --> 00:57:47,331
Did you not realize

454
00:57:47,408 --> 00:57:50,275
that you were sending
these women to their deaths?

455
00:57:50,344 --> 00:57:53,973
But they were new arrivals,
new women were arriving all the time.

456
00:57:54,048 --> 00:57:58,781
So... the old ones had to make room
for the new ones.

457
00:57:59,987 --> 00:58:03,514
- I'm not sure you understand...
- We couldn't keep everyone.

458
00:58:03,591 --> 00:58:06,025
- There wasn't room.
- No.

459
00:58:06,093 --> 00:58:09,028
But what I'm saying...

460
00:58:09,096 --> 00:58:11,860
Let me rephrase.

461
00:58:11,932 --> 00:58:14,799
To make room, you were
picking women out and saying,

462
00:58:14,869 --> 00:58:19,431
"You, you and you have
to be sent back to be killed."

463
00:58:19,507 --> 00:58:21,975
Well, what would you have done?

464
00:58:32,553 --> 00:58:34,987
Should I never
have signed up at Siemens?

465
00:58:47,468 --> 00:58:51,063
Ms. Mather,
they're ready for you now.

466
00:58:53,474 --> 00:58:56,034
Go, go. Go, go, go.

467
00:59:07,521 --> 00:59:10,217
- Where's Michael?
- I don't know.

468
00:59:11,559 --> 00:59:16,155
In your book, you describe
the process of selection.

469
00:59:16,230 --> 00:59:17,822
Yes.

470
00:59:17,898 --> 00:59:21,857
You were made to work and then,
when you were no longer any use to them,

471
00:59:21,936 --> 00:59:25,372
then they sent you back
to Auschwitz to be killed.

472
00:59:25,439 --> 00:59:28,306
Are there people here
who made that selection?

473
00:59:28,375 --> 00:59:30,240
Yes.

474
00:59:30,311 --> 00:59:35,749
I need you to identify them.
Can you please point them out?

475
00:59:48,462 --> 00:59:50,157
Her.

476
00:59:53,667 --> 00:59:55,032
And her.

477
00:59:57,571 --> 00:59:59,038
Her.

478
01:00:01,408 --> 01:00:03,399
And her.

479
01:00:05,412 --> 01:00:07,346
Her.

480
01:00:09,516 --> 01:00:11,143
And her.

481
01:00:12,753 --> 01:00:15,654
Thank you. Please continue.

482
01:00:15,723 --> 01:00:19,284
Each of the guards would choose
a certain number of women.

483
01:00:19,360 --> 01:00:21,521
Hanna Schmitz chose differently.

484
01:00:21,595 --> 01:00:24,120
In what way differently?

485
01:00:28,736 --> 01:00:30,966
She had favorites.

486
01:00:32,606 --> 01:00:34,369
Girls, mostly young.

487
01:00:34,441 --> 01:00:37,239
We all remarked on it.

488
01:00:37,311 --> 01:00:40,542
She gave them food
and places to sleep.

489
01:00:40,614 --> 01:00:45,210
In the evening,
she... she asked them to join her.

490
01:00:45,286 --> 01:00:46,878
And we all thought...

491
01:00:46,954 --> 01:00:49,980
Well, you can imagine
what we thought.

492
01:00:50,057 --> 01:00:55,654
And then we found out she was making
these women read aloud to her.

493
01:00:58,365 --> 01:01:00,492
They were reading to her.

494
01:01:01,735 --> 01:01:06,297
At first, we thought this guard,
this guard is...

495
01:01:06,373 --> 01:01:11,140
...more sensitive,
she's more human, she's kinder.

496
01:01:12,046 --> 01:01:15,447
Often, she chose the weak, the sick.

497
01:01:17,151 --> 01:01:20,518
She picked them out.
She seemed to be protecting them almost.

498
01:01:20,587 --> 01:01:23,147
But then she dispatched them.

499
01:01:26,126 --> 01:01:28,219
Is that kinder?

500
01:01:37,037 --> 01:01:40,200
I want to
move on now to the march.

501
01:01:40,274 --> 01:01:44,335
As I understand it, you and your
daughter were marched for many months.

502
01:01:44,411 --> 01:01:48,575
In the winter of 1944,
our camp was closed down.

503
01:01:48,649 --> 01:01:53,643
We were told we had to move on.
But the plan kept changing every day.

504
01:01:53,721 --> 01:01:57,521
Women were dying
all around us in the snow.

505
01:01:57,591 --> 01:02:02,153
Half of us died on the march.
My daughter says in the book,

506
01:02:02,229 --> 01:02:05,528
"Less a death march,
more a death gallop."

507
01:02:07,201 --> 01:02:11,297
Please tell us about
the night in the church.

508
01:02:19,113 --> 01:02:23,777
That night, we thought we were lucky
because we had a roof over our heads.

509
01:02:23,851 --> 01:02:26,718
Go on.

510
01:02:26,787 --> 01:02:29,881
We'd arrived in a village.

511
01:02:29,957 --> 01:02:34,417
As always, the guards took the best
quarters. They took the priest's house.

512
01:02:34,495 --> 01:02:37,953
But they let us sleep in a church.

513
01:02:38,032 --> 01:02:41,524
There was a bombing raid
in the middle of the night.

514
01:02:41,602 --> 01:02:43,763
The church was hit.

515
01:02:45,439 --> 01:02:49,170
At first, we could only hear the fire.
It was in the steeple.

516
01:02:51,111 --> 01:02:54,012
Then we could see burning beams...

517
01:02:55,616 --> 01:02:58,176
...and they began to crash to the floor.

518
01:03:00,721 --> 01:03:02,985
Everyone rushed...

519
01:03:04,925 --> 01:03:07,359
...rushed to the doors.

520
01:03:09,530 --> 01:03:13,261
But the doors had been
locked on the outside.

521
01:03:13,333 --> 01:03:17,667
The church burned down?
Nobody came to open the doors?

522
01:03:17,738 --> 01:03:20,673
Is that right?

523
01:03:20,741 --> 01:03:22,709
Nobody.

524
01:03:22,776 --> 01:03:26,007
Even though you
were all burning to death?

525
01:03:29,183 --> 01:03:31,208
How many people were killed?

526
01:03:31,285 --> 01:03:34,345
Everyone was killed.

527
01:03:36,890 --> 01:03:38,721
But you survived?

528
01:03:46,600 --> 01:03:48,295
Thank you.

529
01:03:50,370 --> 01:03:54,101
I want to thank you
for coming to this country

530
01:03:54,174 --> 01:03:56,369
today to testify.

531
01:04:00,547 --> 01:04:04,813
I don't know. I don't know
what we're doing here anymore.

532
01:04:04,885 --> 01:04:07,217
Don't you?

533
01:04:07,287 --> 01:04:09,221
You tell us to think like lawyers,

534
01:04:09,289 --> 01:04:13,350
but there's something...
disgusting about this.

535
01:04:13,427 --> 01:04:15,827
- How so?
- This didn't happen to the Germans.

536
01:04:15,896 --> 01:04:18,057
It happened to the Jews.

537
01:04:18,832 --> 01:04:22,233
- What are we trying to do?
- We're trying to understand.

538
01:04:22,302 --> 01:04:25,294
Six women locked 300 Jews in a church
and let them burn.

539
01:04:25,372 --> 01:04:27,602
What is there to understand?

540
01:04:30,210 --> 01:04:33,737
Tell me! I'm asking!
What is there to understand?

541
01:04:36,950 --> 01:04:40,181
I started out believing in this trial.
I thought it was great.

542
01:04:40,254 --> 01:04:43,587
Now, I think it's...
it's just a diversion.

543
01:04:43,657 --> 01:04:46,524
Yes? Diversion from what?

544
01:04:46,593 --> 01:04:49,585
You choose six women,
you put them on trial,

545
01:04:49,663 --> 01:04:52,928
you say, "They were the evil ones,
they were the guilty ones."

546
01:04:53,000 --> 01:04:55,525
One of the victims
happened to write a book.

547
01:04:55,602 --> 01:04:58,662
That's why they're on trial
and nobody else!

548
01:04:58,739 --> 01:05:02,038
Do you know how many camps
there were in Europe?

549
01:05:02,109 --> 01:05:04,543
People go on about
how much did everyone know?

550
01:05:04,611 --> 01:05:08,479
Who knew? What did they know?
Everyone knew!

551
01:05:08,549 --> 01:05:13,213
Our parents, our teachers.
That isn't the question!

552
01:05:13,287 --> 01:05:15,346
The question is,
"How'd you let this happen?"

553
01:05:15,422 --> 01:05:18,550
Better, "Why didn't you
kill yourself when you found out?"

554
01:05:21,395 --> 01:05:24,762
Thousands. That's how many.
There were thousands of camps.

555
01:05:24,831 --> 01:05:26,731
Everyone knew.

556
01:05:35,309 --> 01:05:36,640
Look at that woman.

557
01:05:38,579 --> 01:05:42,140
- Which woman?
- The woman you're always staring at.

558
01:05:42,216 --> 01:05:43,683
I'm sorry, but you are.

559
01:05:52,793 --> 01:05:54,590
I don't know which woman you mean.

560
01:05:56,096 --> 01:05:57,927
You know what I'd do?

561
01:06:00,367 --> 01:06:04,064
Put the gun in my hand,
I'd shoot her myself.

562
01:06:07,407 --> 01:06:09,272
Shoot them all!

563
01:09:04,885 --> 01:09:07,183
Why did you
not unlock the doors?

564
01:09:09,423 --> 01:09:12,017
Why did you not unlock the doors?

565
01:09:15,128 --> 01:09:18,222
I've asked all of you,
and I'm getting no answer.

566
01:09:19,332 --> 01:09:22,768
Two of the victims are in this court.
They deserve an answer.

567
01:09:26,773 --> 01:09:29,571
This is the SS report.
You all have copies.

568
01:09:31,044 --> 01:09:34,605
The report which was written,
approved and signed by all of you

569
01:09:34,681 --> 01:09:38,242
immediately after the event.
In the written report,

570
01:09:38,318 --> 01:09:43,051
you all claim you didn't even know
about the fire until after it happened.

571
01:09:43,123 --> 01:09:45,421
But that isn't true, is it?

572
01:09:46,660 --> 01:09:48,184
Well?

573
01:09:49,729 --> 01:09:50,855
It's not true.

574
01:09:55,268 --> 01:09:59,034
- I don't know what you're asking.
- The first thing I'm asking

575
01:09:59,105 --> 01:10:02,905
- is why didn't you unlock the doors?
- Obviously.

576
01:10:02,976 --> 01:10:04,967
For the obvious reason.

577
01:10:06,146 --> 01:10:08,273
- We couldn't.
- Why couldn't you?

578
01:10:08,348 --> 01:10:11,215
We were guards.

579
01:10:11,284 --> 01:10:14,776
Our job was to guard the prisoners.

580
01:10:14,855 --> 01:10:17,153
We couldn't just let them escape.

581
01:10:17,224 --> 01:10:20,489
I see. And if they escaped,
then you'd be blamed,

582
01:10:20,560 --> 01:10:22,994
you'd be charged,
you might even be executed?

583
01:10:23,063 --> 01:10:25,156
- No!
- Well, then?

584
01:10:25,232 --> 01:10:28,531
If we'd opened the doors,
there would have been chaos.

585
01:10:28,602 --> 01:10:31,366
How could we have restored order?

586
01:10:31,438 --> 01:10:34,566
It happened so fast.
It was snowing. The bombs.

587
01:10:34,641 --> 01:10:37,804
The flames... There were flames
all over the village.

588
01:10:37,878 --> 01:10:41,041
Then the screaming began,
and got worse and worse.

589
01:10:41,114 --> 01:10:44,550
If they'd all come rushing out,
we couldn't just let them escape.

590
01:10:44,618 --> 01:10:48,782
We couldn't.
We were responsible for them!

591
01:10:51,992 --> 01:10:56,019
So you did know what was happening?
You did know? You made a choice.

592
01:10:56,096 --> 01:10:58,826
You let them die,

593
01:10:58,899 --> 01:11:01,561
rather than risk letting them escape.

594
01:11:04,304 --> 01:11:07,899
The other defendants have made
an allegation against you.

595
01:11:07,974 --> 01:11:09,703
Have you heard this allegation?

596
01:11:10,977 --> 01:11:14,037
They say you were in charge.

597
01:11:14,114 --> 01:11:17,140
It isn't true.
I was... I was just one of the guards.

598
01:11:17,217 --> 01:11:19,685
- She was in charge.
- She was!

599
01:11:19,753 --> 01:11:22,221
- Of course she was.
- Did you write the report?

600
01:11:22,289 --> 01:11:27,124
No. No. We all discussed what to say.
We all wrote it together.

601
01:11:27,193 --> 01:11:29,457
She wrote the report.
She was in charge.

602
01:11:29,529 --> 01:11:30,928
- Is that true?
- No.

603
01:11:30,997 --> 01:11:32,760
- Yes, you did!
- Does it matter?

604
01:11:32,832 --> 01:11:34,959
- She wrote it.
- I need a sample

605
01:11:35,035 --> 01:11:39,165
- of your handwriting.
- My...

606
01:11:39,239 --> 01:11:41,571
- My handwriting?
- Yes. I need to establish

607
01:11:41,641 --> 01:11:44,838
- who wrote the report.
- I don't see how that's appropriate.

608
01:11:44,911 --> 01:11:48,074
- 20 years have gone by.
- Take her paper. Approach the bench.

609
01:11:48,148 --> 01:11:51,640
- Compare handwriting of 20 years?
- Approach the bench.

610
01:11:56,823 --> 01:11:59,189
I will not be overruled
in my own court.

611
01:11:59,259 --> 01:12:01,454
I'm sorry...

612
01:12:09,002 --> 01:12:10,799
I'd rather listen to you.

613
01:12:30,690 --> 01:12:32,681
There's no need.

614
01:12:36,563 --> 01:12:38,497
I wrote the report.

615
01:12:52,445 --> 01:12:54,813
Silence, please.

616
01:12:56,116 --> 01:12:57,208
Order!

617
01:13:09,829 --> 01:13:12,457
You've been skipping seminars.

618
01:13:35,755 --> 01:13:38,451
I have a piece of information.

619
01:13:38,525 --> 01:13:41,426
Concerning one of the defendants.

620
01:13:41,494 --> 01:13:44,486
- Something they're not admitting.
- What information?

621
01:13:53,406 --> 01:13:55,306
You don't need me to tell you.

622
01:13:55,375 --> 01:14:00,472
It's perfectly clear. You have a moral
obligation to disclose it to the court.

623
01:14:00,547 --> 01:14:04,313
It happens this information
is favorable to the defendant.

624
01:14:04,384 --> 01:14:06,716
It can help her case.

625
01:14:06,786 --> 01:14:10,552
It may even affect the outcome,
certainly the sentencing.

626
01:14:10,623 --> 01:14:15,060
- So?
- There's a problem.

627
01:14:15,128 --> 01:14:19,155
The defendant herself is determined
to keep this information secret.

628
01:14:22,936 --> 01:14:25,063
- A moment, please.
- Sorry.

629
01:14:33,346 --> 01:14:35,644
What are her reasons?

630
01:14:38,084 --> 01:14:40,211
Because she's ashamed.

631
01:14:41,354 --> 01:14:43,686
Ashamed of what?

632
01:14:49,062 --> 01:14:52,828
- Have you spoken to her?
- Of course not.

633
01:14:52,899 --> 01:14:56,266
Why "of course not?"

634
01:14:56,336 --> 01:14:57,826
I can't.

635
01:14:59,405 --> 01:15:02,101
I can't do that.

636
01:15:02,175 --> 01:15:04,075
I can't talk to her.

637
01:15:04,144 --> 01:15:09,104
What we feel isn't important.
It's utterly unimportant.

638
01:15:09,182 --> 01:15:11,582
The only question is what we do.

639
01:15:13,720 --> 01:15:18,248
If people like you don't learn
from what happened to people like me,

640
01:15:18,324 --> 01:15:21,623
then what the hell
is the point of anything?

641
01:15:29,736 --> 01:15:32,296
Schmitz?

642
01:15:32,372 --> 01:15:34,602
You have a visitor.

643
01:15:47,453 --> 01:15:49,785
Quiet, please!

644
01:15:49,856 --> 01:15:52,984
Gertrud Ballow.

645
01:15:54,627 --> 01:15:57,460
Andreas Michael Springer.

646
01:16:00,567 --> 01:16:02,432
Michael Berg.

647
01:16:05,805 --> 01:16:08,239
Walter Sherman.

648
01:17:42,502 --> 01:17:44,265
Time's up.

649
01:18:03,690 --> 01:18:05,453
Are you coming in?

650
01:18:15,501 --> 01:18:17,492
You took your time.

651
01:18:39,926 --> 01:18:41,052
What is it?

652
01:19:03,316 --> 01:19:06,251
Where are you going?

653
01:19:06,319 --> 01:19:08,844
I'm sorry.

654
01:19:08,921 --> 01:19:10,821
I need to sleep by myself.

655
01:19:56,669 --> 01:19:58,466
I'll just be a minute.

656
01:20:28,134 --> 01:20:30,068
- Nazi!
- Nazi whore!

657
01:20:30,136 --> 01:20:32,969
Nazi!

658
01:20:41,614 --> 01:20:45,948
Silence in the court.
Silence in the court.

