757
01:30:49,955 --> 01:30:53,220
One, two, three, four, five, six.

758
01:30:53,292 --> 01:30:56,420
<i>The Lady with the Little Dog.</i>

759
01:30:56,495 --> 01:30:58,122
<i>The...</i>

760
01:31:02,234 --> 01:31:03,599
The.

761
01:31:05,003 --> 01:31:07,836
The. The. The.

762
01:31:08,640 --> 01:31:10,039
The.

763
01:31:16,548 --> 01:31:17,537
The.

764
01:32:23,315 --> 01:32:26,910
- No letter?
- No letter. Sign.

765
01:33:55,073 --> 01:33:59,100
- <i> You're Michael Berg?</i>
- Yes.

766
01:33:59,177 --> 01:34:03,705
<i>Thank you for calling me.</i>
<i>You got my letter?</i>

767
01:34:03,782 --> 01:34:05,340
I have it here.

768
01:34:05,417 --> 01:34:09,353
As I say, Hanna Schmitz
is coming up for release very soon.

769
01:34:09,421 --> 01:34:13,482
<i>Hanna has been in prison</i>
<i>for over 20 years.</i>

770
01:34:13,558 --> 01:34:14,616
<i>She has no family.</i>

771
01:34:14,693 --> 01:34:17,560
She has no friends.

772
01:34:17,629 --> 01:34:20,097
You're her only contact.

773
01:34:20,165 --> 01:34:23,430
<i>And I'm told you don't visit her.</i>

774
01:34:23,502 --> 01:34:25,231
No, I don't.

775
01:34:25,304 --> 01:34:27,670
When she gets out,
she's going to need a job.

776
01:34:27,739 --> 01:34:30,105
She's going to need somewhere to live.

777
01:34:30,175 --> 01:34:34,475
<i>You can't imagine how frightening</i>
<i>the modern world will seem to her.</i>

778
01:34:37,916 --> 01:34:38,974
Mm-hmm.

779
01:34:42,688 --> 01:34:44,280
I have no one else to ask.

780
01:34:45,657 --> 01:34:48,558
<i>If you don't take</i>
<i>responsibility for her,</i>

781
01:34:48,627 --> 01:34:51,255
<i>then Hanna has no future at all.</i>

782
01:34:54,666 --> 01:34:56,861
It's kind of you.

783
01:34:56,935 --> 01:34:59,199
Thank you for letting me know.

784
01:35:43,081 --> 01:35:44,776
- You're Michael Berg?
- Yes.

785
01:35:44,850 --> 01:35:46,818
I'm Louisa Brenner. Good morning.

786
01:35:46,885 --> 01:35:50,321
- How do you do?
- We were expecting you earlier.

787
01:35:50,389 --> 01:35:54,485
I should warn you, for a long time
Hanna held herself together.

788
01:35:54,559 --> 01:35:58,586
She was very purposeful. In the
last few years, she's different.

789
01:35:58,663 --> 01:36:00,858
She's let herself go.

790
01:36:03,902 --> 01:36:06,962
I'm taking you straight to the canteen.

791
01:36:08,273 --> 01:36:10,434
They've just finished their lunch.

792
01:36:22,487 --> 01:36:24,478
Table four.

793
01:37:09,968 --> 01:37:12,300
You've grown up, kid.

794
01:37:26,651 --> 01:37:28,642
I've got a friend who's a tailor.

795
01:37:31,823 --> 01:37:33,222
He'll give you a job.

796
01:37:35,227 --> 01:37:38,560
And I've found you somewhere to live.
It's a nice place.

797
01:37:38,630 --> 01:37:40,188
Quite small, but it's nice.

798
01:37:41,800 --> 01:37:44,234
- You'll like it.
- Thank you.

799
01:37:46,071 --> 01:37:51,099
There are various social programs,
cultural stuff I can sign you up for.

800
01:37:51,176 --> 01:37:53,872
And the public library is very close.

801
01:38:00,352 --> 01:38:01,649
You read a lot?

802
01:38:04,589 --> 01:38:07,217
I prefer being read to.

803
01:38:11,863 --> 01:38:13,728
That's over now, isn't it?

804
01:38:23,408 --> 01:38:25,501
Did you get married?

805
01:38:25,577 --> 01:38:28,705
I did. Yes, I did.

806
01:38:28,780 --> 01:38:30,839
We have a daughter.

807
01:38:30,916 --> 01:38:34,352
I'm not seeing as much of her
as I'd like.

808
01:38:34,419 --> 01:38:36,944
I'd like to see
a great deal more of her.

809
01:38:39,191 --> 01:38:41,284
The marriage didn't last.

810
01:38:56,708 --> 01:38:59,176
Have you spent time
thinking about the past?

811
01:38:59,244 --> 01:39:03,044
- You mean with you?
- No.

812
01:39:03,114 --> 01:39:06,845
No, I didn't mean with me.

813
01:39:16,328 --> 01:39:20,094
Before the trial,
I never thought about the past.

814
01:39:20,165 --> 01:39:22,326
I never had to.

815
01:39:22,400 --> 01:39:24,664
Now?

816
01:39:25,937 --> 01:39:27,370
What do you feel now?

817
01:39:29,107 --> 01:39:31,439
It doesn't matter what I feel.

818
01:39:32,444 --> 01:39:34,571
It doesn't matter what I think.

819
01:39:36,681 --> 01:39:38,478
The dead are still dead.

820
01:39:45,991 --> 01:39:47,925
I wasn't sure what you'd learned.

821
01:39:47,993 --> 01:39:51,861
Well, I have learned, kid.

822
01:39:51,930 --> 01:39:54,330
I've learned to read.

823
01:40:08,213 --> 01:40:09,805
I'll pick you up next week, OK?

824
01:40:19,224 --> 01:40:21,158
That sounds a good plan.

825
01:40:23,828 --> 01:40:27,491
We can do it quietly,
or we can make a fuss.

826
01:40:27,565 --> 01:40:29,430
Quietly.

827
01:40:31,436 --> 01:40:33,666
OK. Quietly.

828
01:40:36,408 --> 01:40:38,273
Quietly.

829
01:40:46,885 --> 01:40:50,912
- Take care, kid.
- You, too. See you next week.

830
01:43:03,621 --> 01:43:06,112
I've come to collect Hanna Schmitz.

831
01:43:10,028 --> 01:43:13,293
Please. Please, take a seat.

832
01:43:38,590 --> 01:43:41,218
She didn't pack.

833
01:43:41,292 --> 01:43:43,590
She never intended to leave.

834
01:43:49,334 --> 01:43:52,792
"The talk was that a new face

835
01:43:52,871 --> 01:43:56,466
had appeared on the promenade,

836
01:43:56,541 --> 01:43:59,237
a lady with a little dog."

837
01:44:06,284 --> 01:44:07,979
She left me a message.

838
01:44:09,888 --> 01:44:11,788
A sort of will.

839
01:44:13,858 --> 01:44:16,793
I'll read the bit that concerns you.

840
01:44:24,569 --> 01:44:27,561
"There is money in the old tea tin.

841
01:44:27,639 --> 01:44:30,403
Give it to Michael Berg.

842
01:44:30,475 --> 01:44:35,139
He should send it,
alongside the 7,000 Marks in the bank,

843
01:44:35,213 --> 01:44:39,013
to the daughter who survived the fire.

844
01:44:39,083 --> 01:44:41,244
It's for her.

845
01:44:41,319 --> 01:44:44,345
She should decide what to do with it.

846
01:44:47,859 --> 01:44:50,692
And tell Michael I said hello."

847
01:46:08,973 --> 01:46:11,339
- Ms. Mather?
- Yes.

848
01:46:12,043 --> 01:46:14,170
- You're Michael Berg.
- Yes.

849
01:46:14,245 --> 01:46:16,145
I was expecting you.

850
01:46:17,515 --> 01:46:21,212
- Please.
- Thank you.

851
01:46:21,285 --> 01:46:25,745
So you must tell me, exactly what
brings you to the United States?

852
01:46:25,823 --> 01:46:28,917
I was here already.
I was at a conference in Boston.

853
01:46:28,993 --> 01:46:30,290
- You're a lawyer?
- Yes.

854
01:46:30,361 --> 01:46:35,424
I was intrigued by your letter,
but I can't say I wholly understood it.

855
01:46:35,500 --> 01:46:39,527
- You attended the trial?
- Yes. Almost 20 years ago.

856
01:46:39,604 --> 01:46:45,440
I was a law student. I remember you.
I remember your mother very clearly.

857
01:46:45,510 --> 01:46:49,378
My mother died in Israel
a good many years ago.

858
01:46:49,447 --> 01:46:52,883
I... I'm sorry.

859
01:46:52,950 --> 01:46:54,850
Go on, please.

860
01:46:56,721 --> 01:46:58,621
Perhaps you heard.

861
01:46:58,690 --> 01:47:03,491
Hanna Schmitz recently died.
She killed herself.

862
01:47:04,829 --> 01:47:06,262
She was a friend of yours?

863
01:47:07,799 --> 01:47:09,232
A kind of friend.

864
01:47:10,768 --> 01:47:12,793
It's as simple as this.

865
01:47:12,870 --> 01:47:17,239
Hanna was illiterate
for the greater part of her life.

866
01:47:17,308 --> 01:47:20,471
Is that an explanation
of her behavior?

867
01:47:22,180 --> 01:47:24,444
- No.
- Or an excuse?

868
01:47:24,515 --> 01:47:26,608
No. No.

869
01:47:29,687 --> 01:47:33,418
She taught herself to read
when she was in prison.

870
01:47:33,491 --> 01:47:36,153
I sent her tapes.

871
01:47:38,763 --> 01:47:42,631
She had always liked...
being read to.

872
01:47:49,507 --> 01:47:52,237
Why don't you start
by being honest with me?

873
01:47:52,310 --> 01:47:55,370
At least start that way.

874
01:47:55,446 --> 01:47:58,074
What was the nature
of your friendship?

875
01:48:02,987 --> 01:48:05,820
When I was young,
I had an affair with Hanna.

876
01:48:11,763 --> 01:48:13,663
I'm not sure I can help you, Mr. Berg.

877
01:48:13,731 --> 01:48:15,892
And...

878
01:48:15,967 --> 01:48:18,128
...even if I could,
I'm not willing to.

879
01:48:18,202 --> 01:48:20,830
I was almost 16
when I took up with her.

880
01:48:20,905 --> 01:48:24,136
The affair only lasted a summer.
But...

881
01:48:25,710 --> 01:48:27,837
But what?

882
01:48:33,684 --> 01:48:35,413
I see.

883
01:48:37,622 --> 01:48:42,389
And did Hanna Schmitz acknowledge
the effect she'd had on your life?

884
01:48:44,128 --> 01:48:47,461
She'd done much worse
to other people.

885
01:48:52,436 --> 01:48:54,131
I've never told anyone.

886
01:48:58,476 --> 01:49:01,775
People ask all the time
what I learned in the camps.

887
01:49:01,846 --> 01:49:04,576
But the camps weren't therapy.

888
01:49:06,684 --> 01:49:09,414
What do you think these places were,
universities?

889
01:49:11,055 --> 01:49:13,649
We didn't go there to learn.

890
01:49:13,724 --> 01:49:17,785
One becomes very clear
about these things.

891
01:49:21,232 --> 01:49:23,928
What are you asking for?
Forgiveness for her?

892
01:49:24,001 --> 01:49:26,765
Or do you just want
to feel better yourself?

893
01:49:26,838 --> 01:49:30,672
My advice? Go to the theater
if you want catharsis. Please.

894
01:49:30,741 --> 01:49:32,641
Go to literature.

895
01:49:32,710 --> 01:49:35,907
Don't go to the camps.

896
01:49:37,481 --> 01:49:39,915
Nothing comes out of the camps.

897
01:49:42,420 --> 01:49:44,479
Nothing.

898
01:49:57,768 --> 01:49:59,633
What she wanted...

899
01:50:00,538 --> 01:50:04,975
What she wanted was
to leave you her money.

900
01:50:05,042 --> 01:50:07,875
- I have it with me.
- To do what?

901
01:50:09,981 --> 01:50:11,710
As you think fit.

902
01:50:22,727 --> 01:50:24,285
Here.

903
01:50:32,870 --> 01:50:37,671
When I was a little girl,
I had a tea tin for my treasures.

904
01:50:37,742 --> 01:50:42,042
Not quite like this.
It had Cyrillic lettering.

905
01:50:44,916 --> 01:50:48,181
I took it with me to the camp,
but it got stolen.

906
01:50:48,252 --> 01:50:51,744
- What was in it?
- Sentimental things.

907
01:50:51,822 --> 01:50:55,952
A piece of hair from our dog.
Some tickets to the operas

908
01:50:56,027 --> 01:50:59,929
my father had taken me to.
It wasn't stolen for its contents.

909
01:50:59,997 --> 01:51:03,899
It was the tin itself

910
01:51:03,968 --> 01:51:06,596
that was valuable,

911
01:51:06,671 --> 01:51:08,332
what you could do with it.

912
01:51:16,547 --> 01:51:19,482
There's nothing
I can do with this money.

913
01:51:19,550 --> 01:51:22,951
I give it to anything associated
with extermination of Jews,

914
01:51:23,020 --> 01:51:25,614
then to me it seems...

915
01:51:25,690 --> 01:51:29,057
...like absolution, and that's
something I'm neither willing

916
01:51:29,126 --> 01:51:32,857
- nor in a position to grant.
- I was thinking maybe

917
01:51:32,930 --> 01:51:36,798
an organization to encourage literacy.

918
01:51:40,638 --> 01:51:43,163
Good. Good.

919
01:51:43,240 --> 01:51:46,107
Do you know if there
is a Jewish organization?

920
01:51:46,177 --> 01:51:47,940
I'd be surprised if there isn't.

921
01:51:48,012 --> 01:51:51,641
There's a Jewish organization
for everything.

922
01:51:51,716 --> 01:51:54,810
Not that illiteracy
is a very Jewish problem.

923
01:51:56,654 --> 01:51:59,919
Why don't you find out?
Send them the money.

924
01:52:16,140 --> 01:52:18,074
Shall I do it in Hanna's name?

925
01:52:20,077 --> 01:52:21,567
As you think fit.

926
01:52:26,884 --> 01:52:28,681
I'll keep the tin.

927
01:52:33,624 --> 01:52:35,251
Thank you.

928
01:53:27,178 --> 01:53:31,911
- Where are we going?
- I thought you liked surprises.

929
01:53:31,982 --> 01:53:35,110
I do. I do like surprises.

930
01:54:39,383 --> 01:54:42,181
Hanna Schmitz.

931
01:54:46,524 --> 01:54:47,616
Who was she?

932
01:54:50,161 --> 01:54:52,561
That's what I wanted to tell you.

933
01:54:54,732 --> 01:54:56,859
That's why we're here.

934
01:55:05,042 --> 01:55:06,634
So tell me.

935
01:55:18,355 --> 01:55:20,789
I was 15.

936
01:55:23,360 --> 01:55:25,885
I was coming home from school.

937
01:55:27,965 --> 01:55:29,796
I was feeling ill.

938
01:55:31,101 --> 01:55:33,535
And a woman helped me.

